I am only up to the part where she’s discussing zoom camera first impressions. 
I disagree about requiring you to turn your camera on. As a female in a very male industry, I get a lot more done and meetings are significantly shorter when my camera is off. 
If I turn my camera on, it takes more time and people linger excessively. Once I stopped turning on my camera I found meeting became more productive and people stayed professional and did not get overly familiar. 
And for the record I’m incredibly  aware about how people perceive me and I let go of that worry years ago. My rule of thumb is to talk about things I would talk to my mother about and behave as though my parents are part of the conversation. It has kept me on the right path my whole life.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text:
Here is the thing: This woman sounds like she is so knowledgable, but she is not, she is just paraphrasing what she reads online without understanding the nuance. Let me give you an example: At the end, she starts talking about the Big 5 Personality Traits. Extraversion is actually NOT the same as extroversion (although they are correlated). The extraversion trait in the Big 5 theory is "if something good happens, how quickly and strongly do you feel happy about it and how long does it last?" This is the opposite of neuroticism but one can be both highly neurotic and highly extraversion (or the opposite) so being high on one doesn't necessarily mean being high on the other. Extroverts tend to have high extraversion. 
The microexpressions, I thought she was going to teach him something interesting, ended up just showing him the approximately universal expressions everyone is familiar with. I mean she has great social skills but she should acknowledge that she is not a psychologist instead of acting like an expert on every single topic they discussed.

And then the bullshit she made up about "getting more antibodies from people" as an extravert...  🤦‍♀ As a biologist, I almost died inside. She is a confident bullshitter.

There is no baby crisis! There is an income to debt crisis. No one is going to start a family if they have no house or money, cannot afford school and the future seems so uncertain.

To justify, one redeeming point of this:
The outsides needs to match your insides. Ever see yourself in action on a video? For me, it's horrifying at first then just gets in my head. How to adjust my non-verbal? 
Ever notice text vs call vs video vs in person? This is the point. What am I communicating non-verbally 80% of the time that is influencing my connection. Everyone needs to be connected if they are healthy.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text:
Summarize:

💔💬 Crisis in Modern Dating and Human Connection

1️⃣ Today’s Emotional Disconnection
Many people don’t know how to show they like someone—neither verbally nor physically. This leads to missed opportunities for connection, relationships, and friendships.

2️⃣ The Problem with Modern “Dates”
Vanessa Van Edwards, an expert in human behavior, observed real-life dates where most people hid their emotions or didn’t know how to communicate:

Women who were interested but acted cold or disinterested.

Men who were friendly but didn’t go deeper.

Conversations full of facts (“How long have you lived in Austin?”) instead of feelings or passions.


3️⃣ Vanessa’s Conclusion:

> “We’re in a human connection crisis. If we continue like this, there will be no real bonds, no deep friendships, no families.”




---

🧠📚 How Human Personality Works

2️⃣ The 5 Personality Traits ("OCEAN")
Every person has these five traits to some degree: 🅐 Openness: curiosity, creativity, openness to new experiences.
🅑 Conscientiousness: organization, discipline, attention to detail.
🅒 Extraversion: social energy, desire for interaction.
🅓 Agreeableness: empathy, kindness, cooperation.
🅔 Neuroticism: tendency to worry, anxiety, emotional instability.

🔬 Around 42%–57% of personality is genetic, but 30%–40% can be changed with effort.


---

🗣️🌟 How to Be a Great Communicator

3️⃣ Fundamental Communication Skills

🟢 Nonverbal Language Is Everything:

First impressions happen within the first 100 milliseconds.

Be careful not to stare at your phone or hide your hands: that conveys insecurity or defeat.

Showing your palms and maintaining eye contact instantly builds trust.


🟢 The “Triple Threat” Rule:

👀 Eye contact.

🤲 Visible hands.

🙆 Open posture.


🟢 Break the Script:

Instead of saying “How are you?”, say:

“What’s been good today?”

“What are you looking forward to?”


This triggers positive emotions like dopamine and serotonin in the other person.



---

🎭🧏 Universal Facial Expressions

4️⃣ The 7 Key Microexpressions
Vanessa teaches how to identify emotions just by reading facial expressions:

😱 Fear: wide eyes, raised eyebrows, open mouth.

🤢 Disgust: wrinkled nose, tight mouth.

😡 Anger: clenched jaw, tense lips, furrowed brows.

😀 Genuine Happiness: crow’s feet around the eyes, wide authentic smile.

😔 Sadness: droopy eyes, downturned mouth.

😏 Contempt: one-sided smirk.

😮 Surprise: wide open eyes and mouth.


👉 These help detect someone’s real feelings even when unspoken.


---

❤️‍🔥👁️ How to Show Romantic or Friendly Interest

5️⃣ Ways to Show You Like Someone

🟣 Verbally:

Say phrases like “This is really fun,” “You’re so interesting!”

Use positive words like “love,” “fun,” “exciting” to actually create that energy.


🟣 Nonverbally:

Head tilt.

Easy laughter (be an “easy laugher”).

Self-touch (hair, face, lips).

High fives, warm gestures, open arms.



---

🧰💼 Practical Tools for Life and Business

6️⃣ Impressions in Digital Environments (Zoom, photos, social media):

Avoid virtual backgrounds—they create distrust.

Keep your camera on, look at the lens, angle your body slightly toward the screen.

Start meetings with anecdotes or interesting facts to break the ice.


📸 LinkedIn or Dating Profile Photos:

Posture, real smiles, visible hands and eyes matter.

Use objects or gestures that reflect your personality (glasses, books, pets).



---

🤝🧑‍🤝‍🧑 Deep and Lasting Relationships

7️⃣ How to Spot Good Friends or Partners

Define your key values: honesty, depth, respect, emotional responsibility.

Ask yourself: do I feel calm, authentic, and heard around them?


🚩 Watch out for:

Friends who always say yes but cancel often.

People who hide their feelings of affection.

Relationships with contempt: this predicts divorce!



---

🧪🧬 Studies on Personality, Health, and Longevity

8️⃣ Personality and Long-Term Health ✅ The longest-living people:

Are highly extroverted (more social connection).

Are highly conscientious (they build strong health habits).


⚠️ The shortest-living people:

Are highly neurotic (constant stress harms health).



---

🔄🎯 Can We Change Our Personality?

9️⃣ Yes—Partially

While much of it is genetic, you can change about 30%-40%.

An introvert can become an ambivert with practice.

A disorganized person can develop structure and routines.



---

💡📲 Final Practical Ideas

🔟 Mirror & Digital Blackout Challenges:

30 days without mirrors: boosts self-worth based on who you are, not your appearance.

30 days without social media: forces you to seek oxytocin and dopamine from real-life interaction.


🧠 Face-to-face connection generates the best emotions, emotional health, and real happiness.


---

🧩✨ Inspirational Conclusion

Vanessa Van Edwards teaches that effective communication is a superpower. It helps us form better relationships, opens up career opportunities, and leads to a more fulfilling life.

And the best part: anyone can learn it, even those who consider themselves “socially awkward.” All it takes is curiosity, effort, and consistent practice.

comment_text:
47:50 I disagree about the vocal fry. I'm not an expert, and I agree with everything else that Vanessa said, but I think the vocal fry is the one thing that girl did that indicated that she was attracted to her date. 

Vocal fry, at least for men, is perceived as sexy. It's bedroom talk. Vanessa is right. It's not confidant, but that's the point. It's a biologically feminine thing to use physical weakness to gain social power. Vocal fry is a way to do that in a male/female dynamic. It's a show of weakness that invites him to be a protector and leader.

And, if you listen, you'll notice that he starts using vocal fry back. He's mirroring her voice to make her feel comfortable. He's showing weakness to say that he's not a threat to her, and bringing it to a more intimate level. 

So, this girl just gained physical power by getting him to submit/show weakness, even though he is probably stronger than her.

Now, the other response he could've given would be to start acting as a protector and/or leader. 

If they'd been sitting on the same side of the table and were comfortable enough with each other, he might've shown protectiveness by putting an arm around her. 

He DID show leadership by asking her out, though he also wasn't sure if that's what she wanted. He was getting mixed signals. I'm pretty sure he wouldn't have asked her out if it wasn't for the vocal fry.

@21:27 "Breaking the script"... I took piano in high school. Our piano teacher, when asked "How are you?" would always answer with an exaggerated "wonderful", "amazing", "fantastic", or something extravagant like that. One day, one of us said "You deal with a bunch of inner city teenagers all day, why do you say you're doing great?" His response was "It's simple psychology. You project outward what you want to feel inward... I've been attempting this for over 20 years, I'll let you know when it works!"... This basic principal has opened so many networking connections for me, it's ridiculous. It breaks the norm, adds a chuckle at times, and leaves a lasting impression.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text:
So... hm. I agree with what she's saying about contempt, but I don't agree about the expression she's describing. It's not a smirk or one-sided smile. I know that, for me and lots of people that I associate with, that's often a genuine expression of subtle happiness or momentary amusement. And, like she says about smiles, it extends upward into the eyes. It can be the example that Stephen was giving, but that's not a smirk or one-sided smile. That's a disapproving sneer. It's not a half-smile, it's a tightening of one side that, as in Stephen's expression, results in more of a straight line than a curved line, and often results in a slight lowering of the eyelids. Those are two different expressions.
In her own example at 1:33:54, that's still a decent example of contempt/disapproval, but it's a totally different expression than the one being described, as she's tightening both sides of her mouth. It's not a lifting of either side, but a tightening, similar to anger but displaced to the sides, rather than the middle.
I would also disagree with eye rolling. Again, it depends on what else is going on in the face, but it's usually pretty clear whether eye rolling is silly and playful or a bit contemptuous or dismissive. And, I personally, don't find silly eye rolling to be nearly as common. But, again, it's the combination of the rolling along with the brow and mouth positioning. Silly will usually involve raised eyebrows and at least a half smile. And, again with her example, her eyroll doesn't look amused and she combines it with an exhale of exacerbation in "Ugh, you're being so silly." That's a dismissive delivery, implying mild contempt. Silly eye-rolling might be accompanied by a more friendly, higher pitch and a "You're so silly!"

I know she's the expert and I'm not, but I agree with a lot of what she's saying and don't agree on this because what she's describing isn't even what she's doing in her own example.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text: Speaking for myself, I'll take a pretty hard pass on the opening-a-zoom-call-with-an-anecdote shtick. To me it signals someone who is self-absorbed, doesn't care about my time, and isn't focused on the purpose of the meeting. I suppose if the purpose of the call is a blind date then ehh, whatever (I've never done online dating) but it still signals someone too self-absorbed to be curious about me compared with the last meal she ate, which suggests this isn't very important to her. Especially if the anecdote is a breakfast taco. That's so mundane that it's nonplussing, kinda gives scatterbrain vibes. Could also be a nervous "please like me, please share my current obsession" habit, which at least conveys wanting to connect (a good thing) -- hopefully breakable if a more meaningful, genuine connection happens. But for a group meeting or business meeting it would probably annoy me, especially if it triggered a chain of reciprocations.

comment_text:
To the comments that say they're happy that they don't have to worry about all these stuff as they're getting older...I disagree with yall. I don't disagree that yall are getting more happy, good for you. 
I disagree because I grew up not caring what others felt, naturally. Now, I'm 27, and I can't read the room, I make bad impressions, I say the wrong thing (oftentimes) at the wrong time, I express the opposite of how I feel a lot, and many more. I don't feel happy that I have a habit of not caring about what others think. So no, it doesn't get way better for me as I age. It gets worse (if I don't change.) I've lost friends, jobs, and sales because of my lack of care of what others think. 
I assume yall still know how to care about what others think, you just do it unconsciously because of the years of habits. You can still read the room and know what to say without all her tiny details to worry about. But as someone who is socially awkward no matter how I intuitively change, this video is truly helpful. 
I just want to put this out there for people who think "Yeah, who cares, I should care less because this comment said it would be better as you get older."

Key Insights & Takeaways

Personality Is Mutable

Traits are 42–57% heritable; 30–40% open to growth with practice (1:10).

High openness → dopamine seekers; low conscientiousness → habit challenges (1:48, 98:07).

Nailing First Impressions

Begin the moment you’re seen: avoid phones, hidden hands, closed posture (9:08–9:31).

Profile pictures shape judgments within 100 ms; small cue tweaks shift warmth vs competence (10:28–11:09).

Mastering Conversation

Break scripts: e.g., ask “What’s been good?” not “How are you?” (21:36).

Use thread theory: respond with “Me, too” to build immediate serotonin bonds (25:42).

Microexpressions & Emotion

Seven universals reveal underlying truth; addressing fear or disgust in real time builds trust (81:46–82:07).

Contempt smirk predicts relational breakdown; shared activities can repair bonds (93:59).

Virtual & Leadership Contexts

On Zoom, camera on first few seconds, 60% eye contact, and prepared anecdotes beat awkward silence (30:47–32:06).

Leaders pitch with hooks: state your role + “because” reason + a story → invites follow‑up (66:34–69:34).

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text:
If someone asks you if you had a nice holiday.

You answer ' the weather was crap but we had a great time'.

Or you answer 'we had a great time but the weather was crap'. 

The first answer you sound positive and upbeat.
The second answer you sound negative and miserable.
Both answers are actually saying the same thing but it's important to finish the answer on a positive note rather than a negative note.
This is the sort of thing she's talking about. It's not about being fake. It's not about abandoning your beliefs, values and principles. And pretending to like something you don't. It's about being mindful of how you project your authentic self.

comment_text: ​@@AllAboutMusicMovies They're not suggesting that flatter people with fake laughter. The real suggestion here is that you be a pleasant person that actually finds simple attempts at humor funny. If the joke is good, laugh because of the joke. If the joke isn't great, laugh at the failure and corniness of the joke and have some fun with the person in a friendly way. When someone is willing to joke around a bit with you, they're attempting to be pleasant and willing to take a chance. They know not all of their jokes are top-flight. Laughing at a bad joke ... because it is a terrible joke ... is also welcome. Someone who is a snot that just sits there and doesn't respond at all, looking down at the person for a stupid joke is precisely the kind of person nobody likes. Not even intelligent people. ;) Being difficult to please in the circumstances isn't authentic. It is arrogant and unpleasant.

- [01:25:22](5122s) 😠 "Anger" facial expression (tense lips, jutting jaw, narrowed eyes) conveys strength and defensiveness; immediately defuse with shared goals.

- [01:28:08](5288s) 💉 Botox that restricts facial expressions can reduce both positive (happiness) and negative (anger) emotions, demonstrating facial feedback theory.
- [01:28:51](5331s) 😢 "Sadness" facial expression (downward mouth, lower lip out) naturally triggers empathy; it can also physically induce crying or yawning.
- [01:30:43](5443s) 🗣 Naming an emotion (e.g., "Are you upset?") encourages clarification and reveals someone's true feelings.

- [01:36:03](5763s) 🧬 Personality consists of five main traits (OCEAN): Openness, Conscientiousness, Extraversion, Agreeableness, Neuroticism; each trait has genetic components but can still change around 30-40%.
- [01:37:10](5830s) 🌍 Openness describes curiosity, creativity, and preference for new experiences; high-open people seek novelty and adventure, while low-open individuals prefer routine and predictability.
- [01:40:54](6054s) 📑 Conscientiousness measures detail orientation, organization, and responsibility; high conscientiousness strongly predicts career success and financial stability.
- [01:43:55](6235s) ⚡ Extraversion is about social energy; extroverts gain energy from social interactions, introverts recharge alone, and ambiverts fall in between, needing balanced social and alone time.
- [01:47:27](6447s) 🤝 Agreeableness relates to cooperation and likability; high-agreeable people prioritize harmony and often struggle to set boundaries, while low-agreeable people are skeptical, critical, and default to saying "no."
- [01:49:46](6586s) 😰 Neuroticism measures emotional stability and tendency to worry; high neurotics are more prone to anxiety due to slower serotonin responses, making negative experiences feel worse and last longer.
- [01:51:12](6672s) ♀ Gender stereotypes exist in personality traits: women typically score higher in neuroticism and agreeableness, whereas men tend to score higher in extraversion.
- [01:52:35](6755s) 🚩 Narcissists typically score high in extraversion, low in agreeableness, and low in neuroticism, often believing their personality traits are perfect, unwilling to compromise or acknowledge faults.
- [01:54:27](6867s) ⏳ High conscientiousness and high extraversion correlate with increased longevity due to good health habits and stronger social support networks.
- [01:55:08](6908s) 📉 High neuroticism correlates with shorter lifespan due to chronic stress and worry negatively impacting long-term health.

- [01:55:23](6923s) 🧠 High neuroticism leads to chronic stress and anxiety because neurotics produce serotonin slower, intensifying negative experiences.
- [01:57:00](7020s) 🦠 Extroverts have stronger immune responses due to frequent positive social interactions and exposure to diverse immune systems.
- [01:57:28](7048s) 🤗 Strong social connections act as "stress insurance," reducing the physiological impact of stress.
- [01:57:42](7062s) 🚶 Lifelong singles often score low in openness, extraversion, and conscientiousness, making it harder to meet new people.
- [01:58:51](7131s) 🎯 People low in extraversion should focus on socializing through activities they genuinely enjoy, making new relationships a natural byproduct.
- [01:59:47](7187s) 🤝 Personality traits like extraversion can often be accurately inferred from handshake strength and style.
- [02:00:45](7245s) 👃 People subconsciously smell their hands after shaking hands, likely assessing compatibility or sensing stress through subtle chemical signals.
- [02:01:27](7287s) 🎭 Your vibe or initial gut feeling about someone is real and influenced by pheromones, facial expressions, and body language.
- [02:02:52](7372s) 🧩 Trusting your gut feeling about people is essential, as this instinctual sense is often accurate.
- [02:04:16](7456s) 📚 Many writers today spend more time marketing than writing, even if marketing (such as short-form videos) doesn't align with their preferences or original expectations.
- [02:06:20](7580s) 🌟 Finding an audience of like-minded individuals can significantly energize and motivate someone’s work and purpose.

comment_text:
I think one of the most beautiful things to ask someone on a date is: 1. What are you grateful for? 2. What is your idea of a perfect day? 3. What are your goals?
Number 3 can seem a bit intimidating but if you truly know yourself, you'd know even waking up at 5 or 6 could be the biggest goal and accomplishment for you.

As for those saying be yourself. I agree. But what version of you do you want to be? For me that would be a calm composed, patient, and not impulsive attention seeking person, so to change that side of me and being aware of these anti social cues is not fake, it's next level self awareness, it feels weird at first, for months actually, but eventually it becomes your new skin. It's not fake it's evolution.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text: Huh.....okay.....my brain doesn't work this way.....none of what is being described comes naturally. I'm constantly scripting what to say and what to do, with no clue how to get it right. Masking. It's exhausting. First impressions before someone speaks - only if it's something strong like a smile or a glower. Otherwise, I hold off making judgements until after I've been talking with the person. The eye contact.....I know most people want that eye contact, but I truly can't fully hear what you're saying if I'm focusing on eye contact. I need to be able to sit side by side, or at an angle so I can just gaze at a wall or into the distance and focus on the words being said. I'm sure these tips will work great for some people, but for me it's wearing me out and hurting my brain to even try to conceptualize this, because it is so unnatural and my brain works so differently that I just can't understand it. What I wish would happen is for people to not make immediate snap judgements before asking questions and getting to know the person they're talking to.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text:
I could only watch so much (15 minutes in) before I decided that this guest is insufferable to listen to and watch.  Perhaps she had something valuable to teach further into her session here but I decided to not stay for it.   What she does NOT say is that our own and others view of ourselves and others is very much open to interpretation or misinterpretation based on our own experiences and opinions.   What she presents, represents the world view of North American society and does not necessarily translate to the views held by other cultures.  The only universal body language is frowning, smiling, laughter and crying.   Everything else will be perceived very differently across the globe.     An example would be the Nordic countries (Finland especially) avoid unnecessary getting to know you chit chat and staring you down with eye contact as intrusive and uncomfortable.  Living  in the U.K. for 5 years was a real eye-opener for me into how differently people think and behave.  They are much less likely to make eye contact, smile or engage in casual or even serious conversation with you unless there is a very good reason for it.   And surprisingly, many seem to have the idea that they are all naturally shy and that explains their reason for not being more outgoing.  Of course that thinking and behavior goes completely out the window once alcohol has been consumed and the inhibitions rapidly vanish.  Saw this in Germany too with the starchy and reserved people we met falling all over themselves to get to know the “foreigner” after a few glasses of wine or beer, LOL.   Another point I would like to emphasize is that the psychology gurus offer their opinions based more on what they think you need or want to hear rather than on what your personal experiences are and since they have not participated in your life with you, they will always be offering inadequate recommendations.  You are the best judge of your past, present and future.  So undertake the personal journey of introspection independent of the well-meaning but perhaps misguided ideas of others.  And lastly, always be yourself.  There is no need to pretend to be what does not come naturally.  People will eventually see through the artificiality and wonder who you really are and most likely be put off by the veil of deception.   Learn to be either be content with who you currently are or be prepared to strive for a better version of yourself (perhaps making mistakes along the way) and stop paying attention to others’ opinions because the only opinion which truly matters is your own.  Still not sure if I want to give up more of my time to this video…self-help advice from others can be so dreary and oppressive.  Will need to cogitate on it.
.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text: Some of us unconsciously pick up energetic patterns of behavior from our parents who were awkward (but as kids we didn't realize this, kids automatically model their parents due to being in a hypnotic state through age 7).  Parents who are energetically invasive, for example, may mean well but push their energy body forward out of their physical body toward others.  If you grow up around that you do it as "this is normal" without realizing how other people feel energetically overwhelmed or pushed by it.  We think we're just being enthusiastic or interested, but that's now how it feels to people.  Pull your energy back into your own body and keep it there, folks, and relax.  Otherwise to other people your excitement and interest goes too far forward energetically, so it subconsciously feels like overwhelm or pushiness.  And if we have a high-pitched voice, we can practice speaking in a lower pitch.   People subconsciously take high-pitched speakers as frivolous or silly or fawning and even as less intelligent (thus less worthy of respect).   Higher voices often annoy people neurologically, as well.  Sad but true. We can complain about this as being unfair or ridiculous, but it's just a reality.  How do you want to be seen?  Often slower is better too.  I dropped my voice tone and slowed it, which changed my pattern within a few months.  I'm very much enjoying how differently people have reacted to me for years since dropping my voice tone, because I'm registering more accurately in their perception.  Changing voice tone isn't really any different than changing hair color or clothing style or makeup, you're just expressing so as to be seen for what you feel is your true nature.   If you're not ditzy or fawning or dumb, you don't deserve to be mistaken for that.

comment_text:
Thank you fir such an interesting video. 

Speaking of awkwardness: it looks like there are at least two major types of awkwardness - too less and too much communication.

I had a feeling that a typical example of awkwardness would be inability to open up, so the person is way too close for a human contact.

If the major problem is dialling down an unstoppable desire to communicate or to control one’s “golden retriever energy”, then it’s probably the opposite of what I would describe as common awkwardness in communication. It seems to me that it's easier to dial down your energy than to crank it up.

I understand that this is my personal opinion and there are many others on this topic.

it would be interesting to find a guest who is not too talkative but rather too closed and still was able to get out of such situation.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text: Regarding conversation methods, the first principle is clarity - so people know what you're saying. Speaking so fast that speech becomes unintelligible, overly fast, sounding staccato - thus can sound garbled. This means the listener's concentration is divided in trying to discern what is actually said. The risk is that they leave the conversation feeling unhappy, and possibly more so because they haven't felt able to communicate the difficulty themselves - through embarrassment and / or politeness. So they will not be drawn to repeat the process. Someone babbling in a teaching conversation is even worse, especially when a person has paid for a whole course. Frustration could become anger. That can be difficult to contain. Could explode, most likely later. "That course leader/person drove me crazy! Grrrrrrr!". Some could respond with passive aggressiveness. Some could just request the person to speak more slowly. Which is what I'm doing, I guess.

comment_text:
I think she missed a critical thing.
On any/every video call, the most common mistake in "look" one that is more common, (above bad backgrounds, body language, being too close to camera...)
much the worst most common error is...
using the laptop for the call with it sat on a desk.
That means the camera is looking up your nose at worst (when also too close) but is always giving your look a downward gaze - which NO ONE likes.
My screen centre is always level with my eyes, and the camera at the top of that screen is therefore slightly above my eyeline.
MUCH better angle, for seriousness, for approachability, for almost anything, this is much better than the (at best) unflattering double chin exposure lower angle...
and if you need to type while you are on a Zoom - use a separate lower keyboard,  which is ergonomically better for you as well.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text: The comments on this video seem a bit divided. In my opinion as someone with ASD (autism spectrum disorder), these kinds of videos are incredibly useful to me. I really struggle to read other peoples' emotions, and even just knowing what certain cues may indicate has really helped me, but in a professional and more casual environment. It also helps me convey MY emotions as well. While I would prefer to live in a world where people don't mistake my emotions for more negative ones (and vice versa), the unfortunate reality is that we do, and for certain relationships (networking, career prospects etc) that can be really harmful (whether I agree with the ethics or not) I deem it necessary for me to be able to be amicable with others, even if I find it quite exhausting. Going through the effort seems like a valuable trade off in my current circumstances if it means that it opens doors that would've otherwise remained shut.

comment_text:
Glad she acknowledged neurodivergent people. It’s a completely different language for us, e.g. eye contact, facial expressions. Especially opening questions. When I’m asked questions like “what’s good?” or “what’s up?” I actually get quite frustrated with the person because it’s such a broad question and I have trouble understanding what they want to know. So maybe for neurotypical people it’s a good opening question, but for a neurodivergent mind like mine, it sends me running for the hills and I will then avoid talking to this person. 

This is still a valuable episode for me though as I work in marketing and business, so it’s helping me better understand the people around me! Thanks for making it 🙏🏼

You can Botox your DAO (depressor anguli oris) muscles to get rid of your RBF too!

comment_text:
I have a BSc in Speech Communication. I had the privilege of having a STELLAR group of Professors. One wrote her master thesis on the German Jewish Philosopher Martin Bubers Ich Du &  Dialogue philosophy. We learned more fail to engage in meaningful dialogue than otherwise. We also came to understand Nonverbal communication is AlWAYS more impactful than SPEECH. Another of my favourite professors wrote the classic text book on Listening. I often say the most important part of communicating is not speaking, but LISTENING. Paying attention and comprehending. Overcoming  ones shyness or insecurities is valiant but being too overbearing with your tone or coming across as too much of an expert, or modifying,  without manipulating your style of communicating is more beneficial than engaging in all sorts of tricks of communicating. Authenticity in communication is superior to following any sort of someone else's style of communication. The failing with most Americans and their various styles of communication is simply being too loud. THE English well either too reserved or too  overbearing. The worst thing in my experience... misunderstandings that occur by not listening, or one upmanship. Beng told by one of my lifelong friends that they have 15 minutes out of their busy schedule to talk is also disconcerting. 
No 1 wants to be penciled in for having an authentic conversation.

The playful tilt is something I think I need to incorporate more but its hard as a marine Because we usually remain pretty rigid with body posture. I always give off Authority vibes and its very hard to overcome. It makes life pretty difficult for me. I usually only make friends that play music which means I basically require a higher level of function in my friends. Its hard as a high functioner to reach back down. video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text:
To the people who say “just be yourself”—I get it, and yeah, that’s a nice idea. But sadly, the world doesn’t really work like that. We’re social creatures, and we do need people in our lives. Knowing how to act, how to get people’s respect, and sometimes even their love. Not because we need their love to feel good about ourselves, but because people are often the key to getting where we want to go. Like, I need that job, that deal, that opportunity… and for that, social skills actually help. and what Vanessa is doing is giving us tools and tricks that took maybe years to figure out. She’s breaking down stuff that can make life easier for a lot of us—helping us see what we might be doing wrong based on how human nature actually works. 
Personally, I still believe in being authentic. I don’t want to fake my personality or exhaust myself trying to please everyone. But if learning these skills can help me build better relationships and improve my life, then I’m willing to try. I’ve got nothing to lose.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text:
So true. I see a lot of comments with A LOT of likes, who perceived this interview as something negative or "fake". It is unfortunately a trend I see everywhere online, whether it be here on YouTube or Facebook etc. The people who say "Just be yourself, no need for this fake bs" are the ones who don't understand the message of this interview. They don't want to accept that maybe they could improve themselves, and that they might unintentionally send the wrong signals.

I used to be pretty awkward (Not saying I'm perfect, far from it.), but I've improved. I saw how I was treated by other people, back in 5-6th grade was when I reached a kind of "point of no return" I had an episode in class where I showed a presentation of some music. Let's just say it wasn't received very well, and I really wanted to fit in. At this point I realized, it's on myself how I'm perceived. I started to change gradually over time, consciously.
It took time, but I'm much better with people now. I understand some might say I changed myself to fit in and that I should've kept my hobby, the music I listen, whatever they wanna call it. But at the end of the day, I wasn't feeling good very often and I was still very young back then.

At the end of the day, it is definitely possible to change yourself for the better, without changing who you are.
People can say they don't care all they want, and I like to say it myself as well, but we all know it isn't a 100% true.
author: @mich977f

This was fire. I've been working on this stuff for a while now and here is what genuinely made the biggest difference in how people respond to me:

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text: @@michaelshannon9169  Hi. I'm 52. Im far from wise but, for me, I think it has alot to do with acceptance. All of the biggest challenges in my life have ultimately always boiled down to change and how difficult it can be to truly accept change. For me it's been a gradual acceptance over the last 10 years or so that yep... looks fade, health declines, hair goes grey, friends & family start to pass on. I simply can't physically do what I have always done in terms of my working life. I've recently changed jobs to something (slightly) less physical as I was frankly struggling to keep up. I'm now the oldest in my working peer group by a good 20 years... Very weird and took tremendous adjustment! But I realised once I stopped trying to compete, relaxed my attitude towards others opinions, accepted generational differences for what they are and started to appreciate the smaller things in my life my life changed dramatically for the better. The things that used to constantly trouble me in my 30s & 40s no longer seemed to have any real grip over my day to day contentment. It's a simple truth that I have less heartbeats ahead of me than behind so I consider carefully how I want to spend them now. Every age group has their challenges but I guess the older you get the more challenges you battle therefore the challenges become easier to reframe & accept which ultimately makes them easier to face & life more rewarding.
author: @Mountprospect1

comment_text:
That seems like wisdom, but it is not.  It is modern, "young" thinking to believe that how you are perceived does not matter, what people think of you does not matter, and your impression and reputation are not important.

We evolved to participate well in tribes.  For survival, we needed to have those around us believe good things about us and trust us.  We all still carry that in our culture, and it remains true for so many important things in life.  The most important one is our empathy.  Our failing empathy as a culture is hurting us, and if we do not value those things that build our collective empathy, we are in more and more trouble.  With age, we may care less about our culture, but we should still care about what we are leaving behind for our children.

But the only way you are old enough to not have her advice matter is you are old enough to retire and not need to succeed in business relationships, build healthy communities, or interact with people who need your help.  If you're old enough that it's all about you, you're probably laying on a bed pan or resting comfortably in your diaper.

I hear you. But I also think this is more dependent on—like she said—getting what you want. 

I have friends who have never asked for a raise, ever. They could easily be making thousands more a year and no longer struggling to get by if they just asked, especially when they are capable and have been there a long time. They’ll stay in the same role for years and think they’re simply not worth promoting. 

But I’ve learned about effective communication and negotiation. I’ve gotten every raise I asked for, even if I had to compromise. I’ve nailed every interview I got invited to. And I’ve been promoted multiple times, because I worked and asked for it. 

The world won’t give you jobs and raises and promotions, so you need to ask for it. And that’s where these skills will come in handy, otherwise you might end up coasting all your life and wondering what if.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text:
Fair points, especially about the cultural friction and the hollowness of certain social rituals in North America. I get that fatigue. That said, my comment wasn't meant to accuse, but to challenge an assumption I saw in the phrasing. You described wanting to understand others, but also drew a hard boundary around who counts as "worth knowing" based on their communication style.

The thing is, some of that "small talk", while yes, often superficial, also functions as a kind of vibe check. It’s not always about manipulation or fakery, but more like a social probe: a way to gauge openness, safety, or resonance before diving into something deeper. Skipping that step can sometimes signal disinterest or even inauthenticity in their cultural context. So while I personally don't care much for small talk either, I’ve come to see it more as a bridge than a mask.

You clearly value authenticity, and I respect that. I just think communication tools, like the ones in the video, don’t have to be in opposition to that. Used with awareness, they can actually enhance honest connection rather than dilute it.
author: @Sollith

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text: @@Sollith I appreciate you taking time writing your well thought out comment. I am sure it would be an interesting discussion if we could have it over a beer (or something, I am not really a beer drinker). I can see your points. Apart from culture, I think it also has to do with age. When I was younger, I spent a lot of time worrying about how I came across to others. In general, I am considerate, more of a listener (people often end up telling me more than they intended, I think), and I had to learn to guard my boundaries. I am more careful about whom I invite into my life, and the fact is, I value my long term friendships (some as long as 35 years) the most. I find it tiresome to communicate differently than I am used to, I try not to offend, not to hurt. That is good enough for me. Also, I have to say, I am wary of very charismatic, larger than life people. Most of them are narcissistic. I am always more interested in people who are quiet, more reserved. I just find them more interesting and less superficial. Obviously, I am making some generalizations here, but I do find it to be the case most of the time.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text:
🔑 Key Insights & Takeaways

1. First Impressions Matter Deeply
	•	First impressions are formed before we even speak — the moment someone sees us.
	•	People can judge traits like extroversion, agreeableness, and conscientiousness within 100 milliseconds.
	•	The biggest mistake? Looking down at your phone or appearing closed off — it mimics a “defeat posture,” which signals low confidence.

2. The “Triple Threat” for a Great First Impression
	•	Make eye contact within the first few seconds.
	•	Keep hands visible (hidden hands = distrust).
	•	Use open body language — avoid hunching or making yourself small.

3. Awkwardness Can Be Unlearned
	•	Vanessa calls herself a “recovering awkward person.” Most people can learn charisma and social skills with practice.
	•	30–40% of personality traits (like neuroticism) can be changed over time.

4. Photo and Video Cues Shape Perception
	•	Profile photos heavily affect how people judge you online.
	•	Subtle cues like head tilts, authentic smiles, and eye visibility (no sunglasses) increase warmth and trust.
	•	Vanessa recommends being intentional with Zoom calls: camera on, body angled toward the camera, and starting with a warm greeting or a short anecdote.

5. Conversational Chemistry & Connection
	•	Master communicators “gift good chemicals”: dopamine (motivation), serotonin (calm/belonging), and testosterone (confidence).
	•	Create “me too moments” to build rapport — shared experiences or interests foster deeper connection.
	•	Be a “red apple” — subtly stand out from the crowd with unique greetings or anecdotes.

6. Break the Script
	•	Avoid robotic intros like “How are you? Good. You?” Instead, ask:
	•	“What’s good today?”
	•	“What are you looking forward to?”
	•	Use humor or number scales to surprise and delight.

7. Friendship and Connection Values
	•	Identify your core friendship values (e.g., self-honesty, respect, depth).
	•	Reflect on what drove you crazy in past friendships to define what you do want.

8. Online Dating & Digital Impressions
	•	Say more than just “hi” in a dating app message. Use playful or unique openers like “Howdy” or “Bingo!” to stand out.
	•	Be ready with anecdotes and questions for Zoom calls — don’t default to “How’s the weather?”

⸻

💡 Pro Tip from Vanessa

Create a “story toolbox” on your phone with short, interesting stories or trivia related to:
	•	Where you’re from
	•	Traffic
	•	Weather
So you’re always ready to steer boring small talk into meaningful conversation.

I would be very grateful if someone could please give me a solid answer on this: 

The problem I have with learning any topic -- whether body language, negotiations, science, pretty much anything -- is that there are so many concepts, techniques, fine details to learn. How on earth do you know what concept/technique/response to give or use at any given time? 

Vanessa says she's a recovering awkward person, but she's clearly extremely intelligent, and seems to process info very quickly. She can look at someone & be like boom boom boom - "his shoulders are slightly pushed back, his left leg is angled 45 degrees to the left, he's used 3 micro-expressions so far, he's lying about that" etc. She thinks fast, processes info fast, talks fast, etc. I know others too who can process info/scenarios 2 or 3 times faster than I can, & they always seem to know what's the best response at any given time, no matter how many concepts they know.

This video hit way deeper than I expected. I used to think stuff like body language and microexpressions didn’t matter that much—until I realized I was unintentionally giving off “closed off” vibes in social and even dating situations. Watching Vanessa break this down (and reading her book Cues) made me realize how much we communicate without saying a word.

One thing that stuck with me from Cues was how warmth and competence aren’t opposites—you need both to build real trust. For the longest time, I thought being “put together” meant being a little cold or reserved, but I was just pushing people away without knowing it. Shifting my body language, eye contact, and even tone made a massive difference in how people responded to me—at work, with friends, and even just small talk with strangers.

Vanessa explains this stuff in a way that actually sticks. You don’t feel judged, you feel seen. And Steven is such a great host for these kinds of convos. This wasn’t just entertaining—it was legit life advice.

I don’t want to come off as a troll and who am I to judge… but I feel compelled to comment anyway. 😂

They work in a large room filled to capacity with similar programmers where the door is closed and the lights kept low. Plenty of caffeinated energy drinks, Oreo cookies, Cheetos and/or Doritos are provided thus reducing the amount of time away from their keyboards. With sufficient quantities of programmers kept in such conditions banging away at their keyboards it is hoped that eventually they will produce sentient software. These “code moneys” replace the proverbial infinite monkeys on infinite typewriters (kind of a keyboard/printer combination from the 20th century) producing a Shakespeare sonnet. video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text:
I must say that I love your podcast and every new conversation that is brought to the table!  I never leave comments but this time, particularly, I wanted to mention how different I was reading the first date. I never thought for a minute the girl looked like she had  the 'urge' to leave or being closed off with the guy. She seemed nervous but, to my eyes, she was definitely into him since the moment she sat down. Her eyes and facial expressions were showing interest. I was confused when you both were pointing at the fact that she seemed like she didn't wanna be there. It looked like the opposite to me. And I am bringing this up because it inspired a very particular thought. It made me realize that every human has different ways of seeing/understanding and experiencing the world and relationships. We all express, react and read situations different and there is beauty in being authentically you. It's definitely helpful some common sense and finding better ways of saying things but humans don't come with a manual. As long as there is no harm towards others I find it good  to show up as you are. Being okay with feeling nervous at times, being okay with making mistakes, being okay with not knowing what to say. It's part of our  human experience. It's part of learning who you are and who you want to become in your own authenticity, with your own imperfections .. in your own skin. 
I think that analyzing things is very helpful but over analyzing could be the killer of an authentic individual human experience. We should all enjoy more and worry less. 

Keep up the amazing work!! I watch you constantly and I love how this space opens up different points of view and opinions. It's fascinating seeing how we all shape our own lenses to see the world through. Thank you for holding up a place for such incredible conversations and topics!

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text:
I knew people that would use the pocket list of questions and answers. I used to think it was weird and embarrassing because it's not a normal conversation.
I preferred to be original and respond in an improv kind of way. 
The problem is there were days i was just exhausted, not in the mood, stressed, etc. and i didnt feel like being "charming", and that could lead to very bad impressions or at least you coming across as inconsistent. Last conversation you were vibrant, interested and a joy. You seem like a fake person because now you're shut off and cold. 
Thats when i learned its actually good to have a couple of pocket answers and questions. You can use them when you arent feeling your best. I wouldn't say lead with them, that seems lazy and robotic. But if youre having an off day or you just arent connecting with a person it could help. 
Also watch your energy. If you are wide eyed and borderline manic when it doesnt call for it, that is a red flag. Positive energy is great but if youre too "up", you set off alarms.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text: I found myself wondering if this is a matter of being authentic vs inauthentic but another perspective that came to mind is maybe it's more about conscious vs unconscious patterns. You can say it's inauthentic to suddenly take up more space in a room, for example, but if you unpack that a bit, some sequence of events in your life taught you "I need to appear small in a room to be safe" so that is your default setting. So you can ask yourself... "is that who I want to be?" and build some self awareness around it. Tips like these can be helpful but I think there needs to be the connection that how we act on a date, at work, at the gym, etc. is based on so many unconscious patterns running as a result of lived experiences we may or may not even be aware of.

comment_text:
1:15:30  Sending horrible gifts is my schtick.  Its what all of my friends associate to me.  I actually put a ton of thought into it.  

One instance I gave this especially horrible ceramic tea pot with strawberries all over it procured from a yard sale for $1.50.  I selected it to be the vessel in which I would deliver filled with US Walking Liberty silver coins to a couple for their wedding.  The couple decided not to open gifts at the reception and so the next time I spoke to them I asked if they liked what was inside.  Crickets.  They hadn't thought to look inside the pot and had already re gifted it to a mutual friend as a joke.  When I told them what was inside, they both commented "ohhhh... that explains why it was so freaking heavy".  

We added the current recipient to our call and found that she hadn't opened the pot either.  When I mentioned that she should look inside, she made the comment "I was wondering why anyone would give such an odd gift... and why it was so freaking heavy".  We all had a good laugh and decided that the right thing to do was split the coins between the two recipients... but that the pot needed to stay with the latest recipient until she found an opportunity to re gift it.

That tea pot has since been re gifted over 100 times... and everyone who receives it now knows to look inside for the actual gift.  It is the fifth horrid gift vessel I have introduced into the rotation... and they are all still in circulation today.

comment_text:
Here is my roller coaster opinion about this guess🎢: 

Watching Vanessa give people advice on conversations and body language honestly gets under my skin. It is such a bizarre phenomenon for I don’t normally get triggered easily, hell I tend to be annoyingly passive. (Bonus points for the involuntary sting 🐝!) 

I do understand that her point is to underline one’s intentions in order to be read appropriately by the masses. That being said, my interpretation of her results, even when embodied by herself, is that the person I am assessing is being overtly disingenuous and inauthentic. 

I’ll be a tad more negative bellow, please refrain from reading if you wish to stay within the realm of constructive criticism. 

Watching Vanessa relentlessly 
emphasizing each of her body movements, exaggerate her facial expressions, without pause, feels like I somehow accidentally stepped in a class for the visually impaired. The point being that it never stops as her integrated magnifications are always on display, without any breathers to serve as intervals. 

As the expert she talks about how to “perform” a great first impressions yet failed, in my book, to do so herself. (I believe there is such thing as acting overzealous, deceptively seductive and accidentally showcasing too much of one’s hellium inflated confidence.) 

Rant over, note that I myself am a very low vibe individual who remains mildly depressed, same/same needs to resonate at a lower frequency with me in order to vibe. (As an illustrator, I need more clouds in the sky for the sun, on its own, is a bit too bright for my eyes.)

Vanessa here may not be my personal cup of tea but that’s ok, the world needs variety.

At the end of the day I am glad that she gets people to examine the messages they wish to convey, gives them tangible tools to tweak their approach and motivate’s them to achieve their goals.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text:
@ I think you’re placing too much responsibility on others. Why does judging someone based on a first impression necessarily reflect poorly on them? People have limited time, just like you. They have their own interests and commitments. If you leave a bad impression, it’s understandable for someone to decide not to invest further—unless circumstances (like being classmates) keep you around each other.

That doesn’t automatically mean they’re of “low quality.” And if we follow that logic, wouldn’t it also reflect poorly on you for judging them as “easily deceived” just because they judged you? That’s still a judgment—you’re doing the same thing. So it’s not fair to hold it against them while exempting yourself.

Also, people are complex. Someone who misjudged you once might still be a great friend, partner, or parent in other areas of life. You can’t fully understand someone based on a single interaction—and they can’t fully understand you either.

Thirdly, these behaviors you’re calling “fake” aren’t fake at all. They’re skills you develop to express yourself more effectively. Of course it feels awkward at first—just like learning to play football, badminton, or piano. Using body language or social cues isn’t deception; it’s a way to help others understand you better and avoid miscommunication.

And again, if someone walks away with a negative impression, that’s mostly on you—not them. Sure, some people might be generous enough to give you a second chance, but not everyone will—or has to. Not everyone has the time or interest to revisit someone who left a bad taste in their mouth the first time.
author: @AnhAnh-x3q

If you think your personality is great just the way it is, then maybe these types of videos aren't for you. These types of videos are for people who are looking to improve themselves. If you think you don't need to improve then that is fine, but a lot of people want to improve, and Vanessa's ideology that anyone can improve at these things is an extremely positive message. As she mentions, first impressions are extremely important, and a lot of these tools in this video are not 'let's be fake', they are 'I really want to come across well to this person because they mean a lot/may mean a lot to me, and so I need to make sure that is the message I put across'. When she analyses the dates, it's often not that they were honest, it was more so that they didn't know how to express what they were thinking. In other words, their bodies were not matching their thoughts. I have found that often times, when people around us are comfortable, it makes us more comfortable, and so if you can help that process along and make people feel comfortable with these tips, I don't think that is 'being inauthentic'. Energy is often contagious.

Do I agree with her all the time? No, sometimes I think culture is neglected and I have done a lot of research on micro expressions (honestly, Lie to Me was a big part of my realisation that I loved Psychology) and once I read a couple of Paul Ekman's books I really wanted it to be true, but the evidence tells me that the reading of micro expressions is more fanciful than helpful. 

That being said, I think the criticisms that Vanessa is 'teaching people to be fake' are completely unreasonable. She is not saying 'be an extrovert' or 'be an introvert', she is saying 'put your best foot forward', and I for one think this is great advice from a very passionate teacher.

42:53 i highly DISAGREE…. If you know anything about uninterested women, they are never sitting at the table that close to you smiling (in your face) that hard. video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text: I would rather say it's "fake it til you make it". While we all have our pros and cons, it's the consistent struggle to be better in something that improves you and makes you the person you are trying to be. You're not just adjusting yourself to every person you meet, you learn how to generally conduct yourself. Not every person naturally has the same charisma, and some had bad upbringing that comes with bad behavioural habits, didn't learn social cues. Some people stay on the bottom of a social ladder because they don't believe they can get others interested in them, even though they absolutely can be interesting. They just fail to impress others repeatedly and they make themselves believe they are hopeless. But, of course, if you never believe in your act, you'll never make it your own.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text:
@@whatup8107 Thing is this "be present/be yourself" advice really work when you either:
1. Already have the innate appeal and social skills;
2. Making acquaintances with people who don't judge a book by the cover.
And if the first one is a random, albeit still a small chance, the second one is a 0% chance in, for example, a job interview. HR's job is there to profile you. They will judge you by the cover because it is part of their job. Not only your knowledge or skill set, but also how you interact with people, so called "soft skills". Depending on your choice of job soft skills might be not just a good addition, but a requirement.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text:
One can clearly see how her past has deeply impacted her.

Like in a state of psychosis or trauma, she now tries to manipulate her surroundings—not by being authentic, but by crafting an image as fake as possible, just to be perceived the way she wants.

She calls herself a "recovering awkward person," but this behavior does the opposite of helping. It’s like learning fancy physics terms to sound smart, without understanding the actual force pulling the strings in the background.

What I do appreciate is her deep desire to be authentic and loved. But ironically, she tries to reach that goal by pretending to be someone else, se tries to be someone she thinks people will like. But using real communication and real bonding is always superior to fake approaches. 

Her students? The same story. They were never taught how to be themselves. So now they feel the need to perform, to step into roles just to be seen as successful.

And that’s exactly how you get socially awkward people to pay 400,000 times for a seminar, desperately hoping to escape their misery.

But the real misery isn’t about missing skills. It’s about a missing sense of self aout the character you live and embody every day.

comment_text: Honestly, I used to panic if I had to do any public speaking in school. My heart would race, my face would get flushed, my brain would race, I'd speak super fast.... I actually trained myself out of this by just placing myself into these situations and just seeing what works and what doesn't work through trial and error. All of that analysis turned me into an excellent and very natural public speaker, and I can now immediately assess someone within the few first seconds of meeting them from exactly what she's talking about.  You'd be surprised how your words and gait and non-verbal behavior affect the perception others have of you on a subconscious level.  Once you truly understand it, it becomes natural, and your true personality and authenticity does shine.  You just shine brighter.  It also relieves a lot of that pressure naturally shy or reserved people feel in social settings when you know what to do with yourself.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text: @its-really-that-easy  I now teach French to adults. I'm constantly in front of people talking and answering questions and telling jokes to put shyer people at ease.  In high school, my teachers would allow me to present my papers only to them after class because I couldn't handle speaking in front of everyone, but I didn't want to lose the grades. It was that bad. I was a smart kid, I just had zero self-confidence.  I do agree with you that at the beginning, it does seem disingenuous. That's only because you're stepping out of your comfort zone to be forged in fire.  In college, I realized no one was asking the questions I wanted answered, so I had to step up for myself.  Everyone kind of nodded when professors spoke, but many of the things they said didn't make sense to me. I needed clarification or found that certain points needed to be debated.  I'd count to three in my head and start speaking.  All heads would turn toward me, my cheeks would turn red, but then I'd have no choice but to continue. When I'd ask questions, I'd notice on people's faces that my questions may have been on their minds, too. I was just the only one who asked. That gave me courage.  In university, I was experienced enough to no longer have to count to three. A professor eventually shook my hand and thanked me for asking so many questions. He said it helped him teach.  That was the moment I realized my voice was as important as everyone else's, and I continued in my effort to stop being so shy and awkward.  Now I'm anything but. I'm comfortable in my own skin.  If I say something stupid, I can own it without dying of shame inside and without needing to beat myself up for it.  Not everyone is born brave. Some of us learn it.

I’ve studied Vanessa’s guidance since 2018. Coupled with other trusted experts in the field of psychology/sociology. My self discovery truly started in 2016. In these years I put into practice the tools learned. I can testify to these cues taught by Vanessa truly work. And Ive grown into my true authentic self! The key to not coming across as disingenuous is your motive. Checking your true motive with your actions and words will guide you to authenticity. Your internal motives reveal your authenticity. 
When starting to put these tips into practice will feel clunky. It will feel inauthentic. Practice is the key. I practiced with dating for 3yrs purposely not committing, staying single. That practice has me now in a positive, confident, secure place for all levels of relationships. 
I encourage you to look for how this advice could work, and just try it. That’s how I started. 🤓

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text: @@RainyDaySprite I didn’t say there aren’t aspects of what she said that are true and applicable. I do however interpret the advice given as being too focused on creating a perception that aligns with the person you want to create a relationship with and not simply aligned with improving how we communicate our authentic selves. In my opinion, too much of the research on this topic in general is focused on creating a uniform standard for “good communication skills” that ignores how critical the process of learning how each other communicate is in building that relationship bond. It takes true empathy to learn how to communicate with someone who communicates very differently than you, and that is critical to building a strong bond. I agree that self-awareness and always striving to be a better communicator are critical to relationship building. However, I do believe that while this advice may be all some people need to properly communicate their authentic self, there is also a large number of people who would be creating a fake perception of themselves if they were to holistically apply this advice.

comment_text: Authenticity is not removed when you use these tactics.  It just shines through more.  I used to be super awkward and shy, and trained myself out of that shyness and actually learned a lot of her tactics naturally through trial and error, as I'm sure she did too. I remember when I was younger, I thought it woukd be best to change my laugh to appear more "normal". I have a strange laugh, and it is loud as I have a naturally booming voice.  However, it's actually something people love about me. The stupid laugh that makes people laugh. I've had people in stores follow the sound of my laugh because they knew I was in the store when they heard it. It's that... "unique". So you save the good stuff and the authentic stuff. You just remove the appearance of discomfort you feel when meeting someone, which makes people feel good when they're around you. It's more a matter of rounding your edges rather than changing yourself.  Like sanding and polishing a table. It's still the same table, it's just more attractive.

comment_text:
Not everyone is fractured. Identity fragmentation/disturbances are actually a good definition of mental illness, because the person is trying to fill in the holes in superficial, immature ways (attention, validation, fawning, attacking, retreating etc). When one is wholesome, it doesn't resort to those immature means of emotional regulation. It's not about not giving an F, it's about being authentic. Building your own identity and engaging with the world authentically without the immature strategies. Life isn't a movie or a script but in a way the more real you are the better it is and more scenic it is because you will be able to fully perform as an adult in real time. Because the memories you make will be authentic it will progress you across all of the life stages. The mentally ill do not progress - which is what creates the dissonance between their chronological age and emotional ages. Those young ages don't correlate and have nothing to do with an adult life. 

I recommend the works of Bowelby, Campbell, Sartre, Beck and Kernberg.

comment_text: ​@IceHibiscus there is more to this than "just be yourself". Just be yourself is terrible advice because usually the people that get that advice don't really know who they are. What i think people mean with the advice  just be yourself is actually be your mature self. Now this is complicated because most people struggle to reach their confident and mature self and you can be the best version of yourself in one aspect of your life but you may struggle on another. So if you struggle with these things my advice is self reflection to figure out what you can do better, figure out your true goals and wants, take measures to improve on the areas that you struggle with and ways to highlight the things that make you great, healthy eating and exercise are also crucial. People have a tendency to give advice of the end result ie don't care what people think of you or just be yourself but advising people on the journey to get to that point is far more important. I haven't watched much of this but it feels like this person is still on her journey to figuring this stuff out and she is teaching people along the way. Just be yourself is impossible when you haven't quite figured out who you are yet in aspects of your life. So explore, try things out, push your limits, see what you want, like, and hate and figure out what makes you tick. It's not easy, you will go through ups and downs and good and bad points. Sometimes you will be motivated and sometimes you will get into a slump but its important to identify when the slump happens and figure out tools and ways to get out of it and get back to living a better and more fulfilling life. I've said a lot here, it's quite daunting so just take one step everyday to try and achieve it. Last thing is listening and reading information on it isn't doing it. It's very valuable to get the information but just go out and do one bit of advice you hear and don't let it go to waste.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text: Being authentic is very important, but even still your body posture does have an effect. You don't have to be fake to fix your posture a bit. You can be authentic and at the same time have good body language, some people have natural postures that are beneficial and others just don't.  If you practice body language  a little bit it becomes natural after a while. Once your body language and posture becomes natural, you are authentic. So you you have to practice the fake it until you make it. But with enough faking it becomes authentic and you don't have to even think about it anymore, it's just a natural thing that you worked on a bit to get better at. During the fake it stage, yes you have to try and it may seem fake. But when it becomes natural to you, it's not faking it anymore it's the new you. Not everyone is natural at conversations,  but with some practice you can become natural at it. At that point it is not fake anymore, it's just the new version of your style.

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text:
So, this video isn't for you who are comfortable in your own skin and can be present with whatever a person presents and feel good about your interactions. It's for the many out there who were not gifted role models and environments that would have ingrained in them a subconscious ease in their communication where they would do all of what she's saying and more in an authentic and powerful way. It's for those who know that their interactions aren't serving them, aren't allowing for those soul-nurturing connections that they crave for. It's for the awkward (as stated). Our skill at interacting is not that different than another skill, like playing an instrument. Someone who is not well taught or well practiced, who has followed bad advice or been around bad players, is going to sound awkward. She's giving the measurable and observable tools improve upon that skill. 

I do agree that she is too quick to say "don't do that" because it does put the person on edge and that's the opposite of what she says she wants to elicit in people. She could certainly of directed the person with those well-studied solutions without that. Also, as a recovering awkward person, she was awkward herself in this interview a few times. But she's not relying on her personal opinions, she's going off of research, so even if she's not perfect at it, she has valuable data and information to share.
author: @MsSamareh

video_title: Body Language Expert Explains Why People Dislike You
comment_text: @MsSamareh  I appreciate you offering that perspective. You’re right. But it’s more difficult, and a longer process. on some level this teaches awareness of our actions and effects on others which is an inroad to more successful relating.

@@TheDiaryOfACEO  To a very important person in my life—
The style and what you do with these videos just keeps getting elevated to the next level. I love how you’ve redefined each episode this year, especially the one with the multiple economists going back and forth. That one was really good.

But these last two?
Home runs, brother. Out the park.

(Oh—and I almost forgot the one with the crooked cop. Man, that one hit me hard. But that’s a story for another day.)

So here’s my advice:

Keep doing what you’re doing. I’d love to see more roundtable-style conversations. Maybe something like what you did at the beginning of the year with the emergency broadcast episode—multiple guests, multiple inputs, all navigating this storm we call life. When reality hits us that hard, it’s powerful to see you bring in different minds to process it.

It lets me, as a viewer, feel that “oh s*, this is real”** moment.
It’s a wake-up call.
Because when the ones at the top—who’ve lived through this life—are feeling it too, I know it’s time to pay attention.

Steven, I’m talking to you, brother.
You are enabling minds like mine to elevate.
To rise into a 21st-century frequency—one podcast at a time.

See, what you’re doing?
You’re not just telling stories.
You’re giving us the mental tools to storm our own personal beaches of Normandy.

Your videos help people like me—people who’ve been through hell—believe there’s still something good in this game called life.

I know I’m rambling a bit. I’m just someone with deep compassion who hasn’t found his people yet. But I’m rising—one comment at a time. I rise through this storm.

And I know—I will be wealthy one day.

It will be because of the guidance you gave on this channel and others like it.
Because when I was down and out, I turned to people who had a message.
A message that turned my frown into a shout.
That turned that shout into a smile.
That turned that smile into a high-frequency human being.

So thank you, brother.
And you keep doing what you’re doing.

P.S. That section with the real-world dates? Brilliant. It grounded the message in reality while keeping us focused on the bigger picture. Don’t stop experimenting. You’ve got something timeless here.
